ntuition
Although the input is a 2D matrix, it satisfies two important properties:

Each row is sorted.
The first element of every row is greater than the last element of the previous row.

Because of these properties, the entire matrix behaves like one sorted array.

Instead of actually flattening the matrix, we can perform binary search on the virtual array of size m × n. For any index in this virtual array, we can convert it back to its corresponding row and column in the matrix.

Approach
Consider the matrix as a virtual sorted array containing m × n elements.
Perform a standard binary search on indices from 0 to m × n - 1.
For each middle index:
Compute the corresponding row using mid // n.
Compute the corresponding column using mid % n.
Compare the element with the target.
Return True if found; otherwise continue binary search.
If the search ends, return False.

Complexity
Time Complexity: O(log(m × n))
Space Complexity: O(1

Code
class Solution:
    def searchMatrix(self, matrix: List[List[int]], target: int) -> bool:
        m = len(matrix)
        n = len(matrix[0])
        low = 0
        high = m * n - 1
        while low <= high :
            mid = (low+high)//2
            if matrix[mid//n][mid%n] == target:
                return True
            elif matrix[mid//n][mid%n] < target:
                low = mid+1
            else:
                high = mid-1
        return False
